    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-centre-and-angle-of-rotation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
        <title>Centre and Angle of Rotation</title>

        <objectives component="outcomes">
            <introduction xml:id="auto_t6pucldo">
                <dl>
                    <li xml:id="auto_gmpqepvl">
                        <title>Strand</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_u10o41xn">
                            2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_pobb8q88">
                        <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_fmdf038r">
                            2.3 Rotation
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_jrhgxe5d">
                        <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ot162ykl">
                            Determine the centre and angle of rotation given an object and its image
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_734yp7dd" component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Grade Level</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_llj0ubv9">
                            10
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_7ptztv2t" component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                        <p xml:id="auto_lgs69084">
                            40 minutes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
                <p xml:id="auto_k0d70c7d" component="lesson-plan">
                    <p xml:id="auto_wilij9ox"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_o1d45x0p">
                            <p xml:id="auto_q1gtvrd2">
                                <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that the centre of rotation is found at the intersection of perpendicular bisectors of lines joining corresponding points, and the angle of rotation is the angle between lines from the centre to corresponding points.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_u9hhuajb">
                            <p xml:id="auto_npl4irej">
                                <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Find the centre of rotation by constructing perpendicular bisectors. Measure the angle of rotation using a protractor. Determine direction (clockwise or anticlockwise).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_a8rawxi1">
                            <p xml:id="auto_zg2scm88">
                                <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply the perpendicular bisector method to determine centre and angle of rotation for various object–image pairs on the Cartesian plane.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    </p>
                </p>
            </introduction>
        </objectives>

        <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_aet1pws4">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_4nl9nvus">15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_7gaew6qs">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_cghuz3zw">Students work in pairs to discover how to find the centre and angle of rotation by constructing perpendicular bisectors of line segments joining corresponding points.</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_6kp1chza">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_mj2y2je3">Distribute graph paper, rulers, and protractors. Circulate among pairs and ask guiding questions: <q>Where do the perpendicular bisectors meet?</q>, <q>What do you notice about the angles COC', BOB', and AOA'?</q>, <q>Why do we only need two perpendicular bisectors?</q> Select 2–3 pairs to share their findings with the class.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

        <activity xml:id="auto_hl2bd4ry">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_1nfdbwmf">
                   <m>\textbf{ Work in pairs.}</m>
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_uoml8tcq">
                    <m>\textbf{What you need:}</m> Graph paper, a ruler, a protractor and a pencil
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_3xshjnza">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_dv1t51rr">
                        <li xml:id="auto_7gj58g86">
                            <p xml:id="auto_w5igg6kx">
                                On a piece of graph paper draw triangle <m>ABC</m> and its image <m>A'B'C'</m> as shown in the figure below.
                            </p>

                            <image source="centre-angle-of-rotation.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_1k1dcrvs">
                            <p xml:id="auto_38tujb9o">
                                Join point <m>A</m> to <m>A'</m> and construct a perpendicular bisector to <m>AA'</m> as shown below;
                            </p>

                            <image source="perpendicular-bisector1.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_mtm2nf8p">
                            <p xml:id="auto_sq9kxgui">
                                Similary Join point <m>B</m> to <m>B'</m> and <m>C</m>  to <m>C'</m> and construct a perpendicular bisector to <m>BB'</m> and <m>CC'</m> as shown below;
                            </p>

                            <image source="angle-rotation3.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_dz37pclk">
                            <p xml:id="auto_8iz934cr">
                                Now join point <m>O</m> to <m>C'</m> and <m>C</m> and measusure <m>\angle\, COC'</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_xap8t0pp">
                            <p xml:id="auto_oa9ba9f2">
                                Similary join point <m>O</m> to <m>B'</m> and <m>B</m> and  <m>O</m> to <m>A'</m> and <m>A</m>and measusure <m>\angle\, BOB'</m> and <m>\angle\,AOA'</m>. What do you notice?
                            </p>

                            <image source="centre-angle-of-rotation4.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_twt2259s">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ff4a60cn">
                                Share your work with other leaners in class
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

               
                <p xml:id="auto_qqdkcu6p">
                      <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_lgptlhp5">
                    Triangle <m>A'B'C'</m> is the image of triangle <m>ABC</m> after a rotation.The centre and angle of rotation can be found by drawing the perpendicular bisectors of the lines between two sets of points, <m>C</m> and <m>C'</m> and <m>B</m> and <m>B'</m> or <m>A</m> and <m>A'</m>
                </p>

                    <p xml:id="auto_pxyeuo0v">
                      The point where two perpendicular bisectors intersect is called <m>\textbf{the centre of rotation.}</m> 
                      To find <m>\textbf{ the angle of rotation}</m>, join <m>C'</m> and <m>C</m> to the centre of rotation and measure the angle between these lines.
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_ww2x3ici">
                    <m>\angle\, COC'=</m><m>\angle\, BOB'=</m><m>\angle\, AOA'</m>
                </p>

             </statement>
        </activity>
        <figure xml:id="fig-activity-finding-centre">
            <caption>Interactive Activity: Finding the Centre of Rotation</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="interactive-finding-centre-act" platform="jsxgraph" width="100%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/finding-centre-rotation-activity.js">
                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-finding-centre-act" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1"/>
                <instructions xml:id="inst-finding-centre-act">
                    <p xml:id="auto_cv8rzsu5">
                        Use this interactive tool to follow the geometric construction steps for finding a center of rotation. 
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_niuzku7j">
                        Click the checkboxes at the bottom left in order (from 1 to 5). Notice how the perpendicular bisector of the line joining corresponding points (<m>AA'</m>) and the perpendicular bisector of (<m>BB'</m>) perfectly intersect. That exact point of intersection is your centre of rotation!
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_yi25dfg3">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_g2r2mqp8">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_gaorr5v3">10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_qz9fkx37">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_gr9cggvg">To formalize the method for finding the centre and angle of rotation using perpendicular bisectors, and to work through a complete example on the Cartesian plane.</p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Scaffolding Strategies</title>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_rnxe1a37"><p xml:id="auto_gl281wch">Recap the key discovery: perpendicular bisectors of lines joining corresponding points all meet at the centre of rotation.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tflwqbox"><p xml:id="auto_i79fysmv">Emphasize that only two perpendicular bisectors are needed to find the intersection point.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jgkkk2wr"><p xml:id="auto_47n6rowc">Remind students that a clockwise rotation gives a negative angle and anticlockwise gives a positive angle.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_edm2qmny"><p xml:id="auto_9fre7tn6">Walk through the worked example step by step, pausing to check understanding at each stage.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_uzwpvdn2">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_jc8zp0z5">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_aju2pewj">
                    In the figures below, the triangle <m>X'Y'Z'</m> is the image of triangle <m>XYZ</m> after rotation. Find the centre and angle of rotation
                </p>

                <image source="example-centre-angle-of-rotation.png">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                </image>
            </statement>

            <solution> 
                <p xml:id="auto_v56nnfwp">
                    In order to determine the centre and angle of rotation we have to follow the following steps:
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_xkb3k2ta">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_gml7ws2r">
                        <li xml:id="auto_0qblyx5n">
                            <p xml:id="auto_1d3jkwzv">
                                Join point <m>Z</m> to <m>Z'</m> and construct a perpendicular bisector to <m>ZZ''</m> as shown below
                            </p>

                            <image source="centre-angle-of-rotation3.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_0deqjhrc">
                            <p xml:id="auto_c9vppdn2">
                                Also join point <m>Y</m> to <m>Y'</m> and construct a perpendicular bisector to <m>YY'</m> as shown below. Mark the point of intersection of perpendicular bisectors <m>O</m>
                            </p>

                            <image source="centre-angle-of-rotation5.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_rcquzz1r">
                            <p xml:id="auto_myzj9a3c">
                                Similary you can join <m>X</m> to <m>X'</m> and construct a perpendicular bisector to <m>XX'</m>
                            </p>

                            <p xml:id="auto_2jzzhjck">
                                <m>\textbf{Note}</m> You can use only two points.
                            </p>

                            <p xml:id="auto_e8s77etr">
                               The point where perpendicular bisectors intersect is the centre of rotation.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li xml:id="auto_maspwi3x">
                            <p xml:id="auto_pxi62s6y">
                                Now join <m>Z</m> and <m>Z'</m> to the centre of rotation <m>O</m>. Measure <m>\angle, ZOZ'</m> using a protractor. 
                            </p>

                            <image source="centre-angle-of-rotation7.png">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                            </image>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_rl066hif">
                    Centre of rotation <m>=(-1,1)</m>
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_wg3mayom">
                    Angle of rotation <m>=-160^\circ</m> since rotation is done in a clockwise direction
                </p>

            </solution>
        </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_8kniukyj">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_aawe4gqu">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_o9jdqf5r">15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_r1sew1de">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_oeoa74nc">To apply the perpendicular bisector method to find the centre and angle of rotation for different object–image pairs.</p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_b2zljdhh">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_sf5lo5zx">Work through the first exercise with learners step by step. Circulate during independent practice and provide assistance where needed. Encourage students to verify their answers using a protractor.</p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_nweoqune">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_oryrsmou">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_r82a3fyj">
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ouznchu2">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_y0giohor">
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_0lxn9y9d">
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ida6h0u1">
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_8dqpsj3b">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_vjwpjsvy">
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Answer Key</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_dhoyx4tc">
                <alert>Q1.</alert> Properties of rotation (3 properties): Distance preserved, shape/size preserved, angle same for all points.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_zoi8kagc">
                <alert>Q2.</alert> <m>P(3,4)</m> rotated <m>90°</m> anticlockwise about <m>O</m>: <m>P'(-4,3)</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_cs1nubhr">
                <alert>Q3.</alert> <m>A(2,0) \to A'(0,2)</m>. What rotation? <m>90°</m> anticlockwise about origin.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_p9j60gcy">
                <alert>Q4.</alert> Why is shape preserved? Every point moves the same angle, distance from centre unchanged.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8yc5hsoz">
                <alert>Q5.</alert> <m>P(1,0) \to P'(-1,0)</m>. Angle? <m>180°</m>.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

        <exercises xml:id="exercises-centre-and-angle-of-rotation">

        <exercise xml:id="auto_7945vncx">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_khc1yqpd">
                    In the figure below, rectangle <m>A'B'C'D'</m> is the image of rectangle <m>ABCD</m> under a rotation, centre <m>O</m>
                </p>

                <image source="image-object-rectangle.png">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                </image>

                <p xml:id="auto_2kequnq4">
                   (a). By construction,find and label the centre <m>O</m> of roration.
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_jywnm2jg">
                    (b) Determine the angle of rotation.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
            
        </exercises>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-checkpoint.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table xml:id="auto_klvcskoz">
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Use physical rotation (tracing paper on pin). Start with <m>180°</m> only. Provide grid paper. Colour-code object/image. Use a step-by-step rotation checklist.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Complete all three rotation rules. Find centre using perpendicular bisectors. Verify properties by measurement.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Rotation about a point other than the origin. Composition of rotations. Prove rotation preserves distance. Rotation matrices.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Extension Activities</title>
            <ol>
                <li xml:id="auto_3ublev3s">
                    <p xml:id="auto_xkszwq3e">
                        Rotate <m>\triangle (1,2),(3,2),(2,4)</m> by <m>90°</m> CW about <m>(1,1)</m>.
                        Translate to origin: <m>(0,1),(2,1),(1,3)</m>.
                        Apply <m>(x,y) \to (y,-x)</m>: <m>(1,0),(1,-2),(3,-1)</m>.
                        Translate back: <m>(2,1),(2,-1),(4,0)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_v3rccfuq">
                    <p xml:id="auto_hjxy1ie5">
                        Two successive <m>90°</m> rotations about different centres. First about <m>O(0,0)</m>: <m>(1,0) \to (0,1)</m>. Then about <m>(2,0)</m>: translate <m>(0,1) \to (-2,1)</m>, rotate <m>\to (1,2)</m>, translate back <m>\to (3,2)</m>. What single transformation? Investigate.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_uxxz4c6i">
                    <p xml:id="auto_qkz3768d">
                        Prove: composition of rotation <m>\alpha</m> then <m>\beta</m> about the same centre <m>= </m> rotation <m>\alpha + \beta</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>
        
</subsubsection>